<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="sa0021i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="sa" href="#sa0021i">SA (VI.A) </a>: <a href="../../ff/fnbs/ssaall.htm#sa0021i"> 021(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Once upon a time.</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I have been careful to preserve the balanced sentences with which the tales open; the tautology and the prose-rhyme serving to attract attention, e.g., &ldquo;In days of yore and in times long gone before there was a King,&rdquo; etc.; in England where we strive not to waste words this becomes &ldquo;<mark>Once upon a time</mark>.&rdquo; The closings also are artfully calculated, by striking a minor chord after the rush and hurry of the incidents, to suggest repose: &ldquo;And they led the most pleasurable of lives and the most delectable, till there came to them the Destroyer of delights and the Severer of societies and they became as though they had never been.&rdquo; Place this by the side of Boccaccio&apos;s favourite formulae: Egli conquisto poi la Scozia, e funne re coronato (ii, 3); Et onorevolmente visse infino alia fine (ii, 4); Molte volte goderono del loro amore: Iddio faccia noi goder del nostro (iii, 6) : E cosi nella sua grossezza si rimase e ancor vi si sta (vi, 8). We have further docked this tail into: &ldquo;And they lived happily ever after.&rdquo; <small> Richard Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo; in <a name="RB01" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RB01"><cite title="source">1000 Nights and 1 Night</cite></a> (Denver, 1919) x.162-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cf <cite>FW</cite> 20.23f (BL-476a-146), probably not from this notebook. </mm> </dd></dl>
